## Advanced Topic 1: The Empty Interface (`any`)

Sometimes you want a function to accept **absolutely anything** — an int, a string, a struct.

In C++, you'd use `void*` or templates. In Go, you use `any` (alias for `interface{}`).

Because `any` requires **zero methods**, every single type in Go automatically implements it!

```go
func PrintAnything(item any) {
    fmt.Printf("Value: %v | Type: %T\n", item, item)
}

func main() {
    PrintAnything(42)              // Value: 42 | Type: int
    PrintAnything("Hello")         // Value: Hello | Type: string
    PrintAnything(3.14)            // Value: 3.14 | Type: float64
    PrintAnything([]int{1, 2, 3})  // Value: [1 2 3] | Type: []int
}
```

---

## Advanced Topic 2: Type Assertions (Casting)

When you receive an `any`, Go no longer knows the original type. To use it as its real type, you need a **Type Assertion** (Go's version of `dynamic_cast`).

```go
func ProcessItem(item any) {
    // Safe assertion with the "comma ok" pattern
    str, ok := item.(string)

    if ok {
        fmt.Println("It's a string:", str)
    } else {
        fmt.Println("Not a string!")
    }
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> If you assert **without** the `ok` check and the type is wrong, Go will **panic** (crash):
> ```go
> str := item.(string)  // PANICS if item is not a string!
> ```
> Always use the `value, ok := item.(Type)` pattern to be safe.

---

## Advanced Topic 3: Type Switch (Switch on Type)

When you have an `any` and need to handle multiple possible types, use a **Type Switch**. This replaces a chain of `dynamic_cast` checks in C++.

```go
func Describe(item any) {
    switch v := item.(type) {
    case int:
        fmt.Println("Integer:", v)
    case string:
        fmt.Println("String of length", len(v), ":", v)
    case float64:
        fmt.Println("Float:", v)
    case bool:
        fmt.Println("Boolean:", v)
    default:
        fmt.Printf("Unknown type: %T\n", v)
    }
}

func main() {
    Describe(42)        // Integer: 42
    Describe("hello")   // String of length 5 : hello
    Describe(true)      // Boolean: true
}
```

---

## Advanced Topic 4: Interface Composition (Embedding Interfaces)

Just like you can embed structs inside structs, you can **embed interfaces inside interfaces** to build bigger contracts from smaller ones.

**C++ has no equivalent for this.** This is unique to Go.

```go
// Small, focused interfaces
type Reader interface {
    Read(data []byte) (int, error)
}

type Writer interface {
    Write(data []byte) (int, error)
}

// Composed interface — requires BOTH Read and Write
type ReadWriter interface {
    Reader
    Writer
}
```

Any struct that has both `Read()` and `Write()` methods automatically satisfies `ReadWriter`, `Reader`, AND `Writer` — all three at once!

> [!TIP]
> **Go Best Practice:** Keep interfaces small (1-2 methods). Then compose them when you need bigger contracts. Go's standard library follows this pattern everywhere (`io.Reader`, `io.Writer`, `io.ReadWriter`).

---

## Advanced Topic 5: Multiple Interface Implementation

A single struct can satisfy **multiple interfaces** at once, without declaring any of them.

```go
type Saver interface {
    Save() error
}

type Loader interface {
    Load() error
}

// Database satisfies BOTH Saver and Loader
type Database struct {
    Name string
}

func (db *Database) Save() error {
    fmt.Println("Saving to", db.Name)
    return nil
}

func (db *Database) Load() error {
    fmt.Println("Loading from", db.Name)
    return nil
}

// Can be passed to functions expecting Saver OR Loader
func BackupData(s Saver)  { s.Save() }
func RestoreData(l Loader) { l.Load() }
```

---

## Advanced Topic 6: The `Stringer` Interface (Go's `toString`)

In C++, you override `operator<<` to print objects. In Java, you override `toString()`.

In Go, the `fmt` package checks if your type implements the `Stringer` interface:

```go
// This interface is defined in the "fmt" package
type Stringer interface {
    String() string
}
```

If your struct has a `String() string` method, `fmt.Println` will automatically use it!

```go
type Player struct {
    Name  string
    Score int
}

// Implement Stringer
func (p *Player) String() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("Player{%s, Score: %d}", p.Name, p.Score)
}

func main() {
    p := &Player{Name: "Divyansh", Score: 9500}
    fmt.Println(p) // Output: Player{Divyansh, Score: 9500}
    // Without String(), it would print: &{Divyansh 9500}
}
```

---

## Advanced Topic 7: The `error` Interface

Go does NOT have `try/catch/throw`. Instead, errors are just values that implement the built-in `error` interface:

```go
// Built into Go — you don't define this yourself
type error interface {
    Error() string
}
```

You can create custom errors by simply making a struct with an `Error() string` method:

```go
type InsufficientFundsError struct {
    Balance float64
    Amount  float64
}

func (e *InsufficientFundsError) Error() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("cannot withdraw $%.2f: only $%.2f available", e.Amount, e.Balance)
}

func Withdraw(balance, amount float64) error {
    if amount > balance {
        return &InsufficientFundsError{Balance: balance, Amount: amount}
    }
    return nil // nil means "no error"
}

func main() {
    err := Withdraw(100, 500)
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Println("Error:", err) // Error: cannot withdraw $500.00: only $100.00 available
    }
}
```

---

## ⚠️ Common Gotcha: Pointer vs Value Receivers with Interfaces

This is the **#1 mistake** beginners make with Go interfaces:

```go
type Shape interface {
    Area() float64
}

type Circle struct{ Radius float64 }

// Method defined with POINTER receiver
func (c *Circle) Area() float64 {
    return 3.14 * c.Radius * c.Radius
}

func main() {
    var s Shape

    s = &Circle{Radius: 5}  // ✅ Works — pointer satisfies pointer receiver
    s = Circle{Radius: 5}   // ❌ COMPILE ERROR — value does NOT satisfy pointer receiver
}
```

**The Rule:**
| Method Receiver | Can pass `Value`? | Can pass `&Pointer`? |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Value `(c Circle)` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Pointer `(c *Circle)` | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |

If your methods use pointer receivers, you **must** pass a pointer (`&Circle{}`) to the interface.

---

## Summary: Polymorphism Checklist

| Rule | How to Apply in Go |
| :--- | :--- |
| Define a contract | `type Name interface { ... }` |
| Implement the interface | Just write the methods. No `implements` keyword! |
| Polymorphic function | Use the interface type as the parameter: `func Do(s Shape)` |
| Accept everything | Use `any` (alias for `interface{}`) |
| Cast back to original type | Type Assertion: `value, ok := x.(ConcreteType)` |
| Handle multiple types | Type Switch: `switch v := x.(type) { ... }` |
| Combine small interfaces | Interface Embedding: `type RW interface { Reader; Writer }` |
| Custom printing | Implement `String() string` (the `Stringer` interface) |
| Custom errors | Implement `Error() string` (the `error` interface) |
| Pointer receivers? | You **must** pass `&Struct{}`, not `Struct{}` |
